<subSubSection pageId="55" pageNumber="456" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1437,942,1873]" pageId="55" pageNumber="456">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1704,1729]" pageId="55" pageNumber="456">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific name is from the Latin for “glass”, referring to the clean and hyaline wing apex of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="55" pageNumber="456" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1437,942,1873]" pageId="55" pageNumber="456">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,1776,1801]" pageId="55" pageNumber="456">Comments:</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[348,586,1776,1801]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="456">
Cardiacepala 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2018" box="[511,586,1777,1800]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitrata">vitrata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
differs from all congeners due to the hyaline wing apex. This species is somewhat similar to 
<emphasis box="[401,516,1813,1836]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="456">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Cresson" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[401,512,1813,1836]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="picina">C. picina</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
however the combination of a uniformly dark brown mid femur and a clear corssvein r-m (without black spot) is also remarkable.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
